Rethink Afghanistan (DVD9, 2009)

16:9 NTSC, Runtime: 75 minutes + bonus  

&quot; This is not some faraway place.. this is my home! &quot;

Before our invasion, in the fall of 2001, Afghanistan never experienced a suicide attack in it's history. The mere presence of foreign soldiers fighting a war in Afghanistan is probably the single most important factor in the resurgence of the Taliban.

As part of the filmaking process, acclaimed Director Robert Greenwald (Iraq for Sale: The War Profiteers, Outfoxed, Wal-Mart: The High Cost of Low Price) traveled to Afghanistan to meet with and interview members of Afghanistan's parliament, bloggers, women's rights organizations, and groups committed to the peace movement.

&quot; We are going after ethnic Pashtuns who are fighting the central government in Kabul. We are in the middle of a civil-war. We are fighting a civil-war.. We are fighting to build a nation in Afghanistan, a nation that maybe the Afghans don't want. &quot;

If this film doesn't break your heart, then you haven't one to break.

Manhattanites could have been leaping from the burning embers of tradetower-esque buildings all day and night since 9/11, and it wouldn't have added up to the civilian deaths in Afghanistan, or Iraq, or Libya, nor Syria, respectively.

